
Docker Images in Detail :

Docker Image is a read-only template used to create containers in Docker.

Think of it like:
Image = Blueprint / Template / Snapshot of an application
Container = Running instance of that image

Example:
NGINX image → can create many NGINX containers
Ubuntu image → can create Ubuntu containers


Imagine you have a cake recipe:

Recipe = Image
Baked cake = Container

You can use one recipe many times to create many cakes.

Docker Image Architecture
+-----------------------------------+
| Docker Image                      |
|-----------------------------------|
| App Code                          |
| Runtime (Java / Python / Node.js) |
| Libraries                         |
| Dependencies                      |
| Config Files                      |
| OS Base Layer                     |
+-----------------------------------+

Characteristics of Docker Images:
1. Read Only
2. Portable
3. Reusable
4. Versioned

Image Layers :
Docker images are built in layers.

Example:

Layer 1 → Ubuntu Base OS
Layer 2 → Install Java
Layer 3 → Copy App Files
Layer 4 → Start Command

Benefits:
✅ Faster builds
✅ Layer caching
✅ Smaller updates
✅ Reuse layers

Diagram of Layers
+----------------------+
| App Layer            |
+----------------------+
| Dependencies Layer   |
+----------------------+
| Runtime Layer        |
+----------------------+
| Base OS Layer        |
+----------------------+

Where Images Come From:
Public Registry

Docker Hub
-> docker pull nginx
-> docker pull mysql

Important Docker Image Commands:

Pull Image: Download image from registry.
           - docker pull nginx

View Images:show pulled images and ther details
           -docker images

Build Image :Build image from Dockerfile.
            -docker build -t myapp:v1 .

Remove Image: delete the image created
            -docker rmi nginx

Inspect Image:Detailed metadata.
            -docker inspect nginx
