Docker Containers:
Docker Container is a lightweight, isolated runtime environment where an application runs using resources of the host system.
Think simply:
Image = Blueprint / TemplateContainer = Running App created from image
Example:

NGINX image → run container hosting website

MySQL image → run database container


What Exactly Is a Container?
A container packages:


Application code:
Runtime (Java, Node.js, Python, etc.)
Libraries
Dependencies
Environment variables
Startup command

It runs consistently on:
Developer laptop
Test server
Production servers
Cloud like Amazon Web Services

Container Architecture
-------+| Docker Container||--------|| Application Process|| Runtime / Libraries|| Dependencies || Writable Layer  |+------------+| Shared Host OS Kernel |+---------+| Host Server|+-----------------------------------+
Unlike VMs, containers share the host OS kernel, so they are fast and lightweight.

How Container Is Created
Docker Image  ---> docker run ---> Container
Example:
        docker run -d -p 80:80 nginx
Flow:

Docker CLI sends request
Docker Daemon checks image
Creates writable layer
Attaches network


Starts main process
Returns container ID

Important Container Features
1. Lightweight
Starts in seconds.
2. Isolated
Each container has separate:
Filesystem
Process space
Network namespace
3. Portable
Same behavior everywhere.
4. Scalable
Run many containers quickly.

Container Lifecycle
Created → Running → Paused → Stopped → Removed
Commands:
docker create nginxdocker start <id>docker stop <id>docker rm <id>

Important Docker Container Commands:
Run Container
            - docker run -d --name web -p 80:80 nginx
List Running Containers
                       - docker ps
List All Containers
            - docker ps -a
Stop Container
            - docker stop web
Start Again
             - docker start web
Delete Container
             - docker rm web
Logs
             - docker logs web
Execute Inside Container
             - docker exec -it web /bin/bash

Container Ports
Applications inside container expose internal ports.
Example:
            - docker run -p 8080:80 nginx
Meaning:
Host Port 8080 → Container Port 80
Users access host server port.


Use Docker Volume:
             -docker run -v mysql-data:/var/lib/mysql mysql




